College, and BYU especially, has created incredible stress, competition, and much difficulty for the average student. As an individual who deals with anxiety and depression, college pulls me past my limits and causes negative repercussions. Despite the measures I’ve taken between taking fluoxetine and meeting regularly with a professional psychologist, BYU remains often more than I can bear. Between all this, video games have provided a needed escape from reality where I can actually feel successful in figuring out puzzles and completing challenges. There aren’t time limits. I can fail, but the failures don’t decrease my eventual success. In college, failures affect your grade. They are final. The only way to fix them is not a redo, it’s hoping for the best in future assignments. And if the course itself is failed, a lot of money is put towards trying again. Failure doesn’t feel like an option, because an academic failure is also a financial failure, and that causes tremendous spirals.
